{"id": "b83c65caff214d3ebee0b60eccab33f5", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 16:46:31", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "Building on the compelling direction already laid out—particularly the emphasis on *contextual intention inference* as a central challenge—I’d like to refine and deepen the research focus toward a more integrated, cognitively-grounded framework: **\"Gesture-Enhanced Handwriting with Contextual Insertion Mechanics for Intention-Aware Editing of Machine-Translated Text.\"**\n\nThe core insight we’re advancing is that current post-editing interfaces treat correction as a *textual* task, but users naturally think in terms of *action and intent*. When someone scribbles over a mistranslated phrase or draws an arrow to insert a word, they’re not just modifying text—they’re expressing semantic intent (e.g., “this word doesn’t belong,” “this concept was mistranslated,” “I meant the other sense of this homonym”). Our system should decode not just *what* was written or crossed out, but *why*, based on gesture form, linguistic context, and translation provenance.\n\nTo achieve this, I propose a three-layer architecture:\n\n1. **Multimodal Gesture Parsing Layer**:  \n   Use spatiotemporal convolutional networks (or Transformer-based sequence models) to classify low-level gestures—scratch-outs, circling, overwriting, insertion arcs—from pen input. Crucially, this layer must distinguish *intentional* editing gestures from noise (e.g., hesitation marks, underlining for emphasis), using velocity, pressure, and trajectory curvature as features.\n\n2. **Contextual Intent Inference Engine**:  \n   This is where innovation lies. We integrate:\n   - Syntactic role of the target token/phrase,\n   - Attention weights from the original MT model,\n   - Bidirectional alignment data (source-to-target and back),\n   - Local discourse structure (e.g., named entities, clause boundaries),\n   to disambiguate whether a scratch-out means *delete*, *re-translate*, or *replace with synonym*.  \n   For example, scratching out a noun preceded by a determiner might trigger a re-translation of the entire noun phrase rather than deletion—especially if the source language had a compound structure lost in translation.\n\n3. **Insertion Field Dynamics with Fluid Layout Adaptation**:  \n   Once a deletion or modification is inferred, the interface must support natural re-entry. Here, “contextual insertion mechanics” go beyond caret positioning: imagine dynamic blank spaces opening up via gesture-triggered layout morphing (e.g., drawing a “+” sign expands an inline insertion field). The system could suggest plausible replacements via lightweight incremental translation conditioned on both the source segment and the user’s prior corrections (leveraging meta-learning for personalization).\n\nA key innovation would be **gesture-conditioned latent action spaces**—where each recognized gesture maps not to a fixed command, but to a distribution over possible editing actions, resolved dynamically through contextual priors. This moves us from rule-based gesture mapping to *intent-aware interaction*, closing the loop between motor expression and semantic repair.\n\nFor validation, we could design a user study comparing our system against standard keyboard-based post-editing and basic handwriting input, measuring:\n- Cognitive load (via NASA-TLX),\n- Edit precision (did the system correctly interpret intent?),\n- Translation adequacy and fluency (post-editing quality),\n- User trust and perceived agency.\n\nApplications extend far beyond note-taking: real-time diplomacy, cross-lingual journalism, inclusive education for deaf/hard-of-hearing multilingual learners who rely on written forms. Moreover, by treating the user as a *co-author* with expressive control, we align with broader AI ethics goals—augmentation over automation.\n\nSo to sharpen the proposal: **Should our central contribution be the *contextual gesture-to-intent resolution model*, positioned as a new paradigm for human-in-the-loop neural machine translation?** That seems both technically novel and aligned with our team’s strengths in multimodal learning and interactive AI.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
{"id": "0064e6b42f1e43e1925f6b6481190991", "timestamp": "2025-12-10 16:46:41", "name": "Scientist0", "content": "**Summary of Scientist0's Contribution:**\n\nScientist0 proposes refining the research focus to center on **\"Gesture-Enhanced Handwriting with Contextual Insertion Mechanics for Intention-Aware Editing of Machine-Translated Text,\"** positioning *contextual intention inference* as the core innovation. The key advancement is shifting from treating post-editing as a textual task to interpreting user gestures as expressions of semantic intent.\n\nA **three-layer architecture** is introduced:\n1. **Multimodal Gesture Parsing Layer**: Uses spatiotemporal models to classify intentional editing gestures (e.g., scratch-outs, insertion arcs) while filtering noise using pen dynamics.\n2. **Contextual Intent Inference Engine**: Integrates syntactic roles, MT attention weights, bidirectional alignment, and discourse structure to interpret the *intent* behind gestures (e.g., delete vs. re-translate), enabling semantically grounded corrections.\n3. **Insertion Field Dynamics**: Enables fluid text re-entry through gesture-triggered layout changes (e.g., \"+\" opening an editable field) and suggests context-aware replacements via incremental translation and meta-learning for personalization.\n\nA novel concept—**gesture-conditioned latent action spaces**—is proposed, where gestures map to probabilistic distributions over editing actions, resolved dynamically by context, moving beyond rigid command mappings.\n\nFor evaluation, a user study is suggested comparing the system against keyboard-based and basic handwriting interfaces, measuring cognitive load, edit precision, translation quality, and user trust.\n\nThe broader impact includes applications in diplomacy, journalism, and inclusive education, emphasizing human agency in AI-mediated translation.\n\n**Key Decision Point Raised:**  \nShould the central contribution be positioned as a new paradigm in human-in-the-loop NMT—the *contextual gesture-to-intent resolution model*? This would highlight technical novelty and align with the team’s expertise in multimodal and interactive AI.", "role": "assistant", "url": null, "metadata": null, "_colored_name": "\u001b[96mScientist0\u001b[0m"}
